[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Cross-System Care-Journey Coordination With Longitudinal State, Multi-Institution Integration, and Conversational Surface
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical and operational workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-EHR-message-and-spreadsheet problem for several decades. The reason is structural, and is worth dwelling on because the structural problem is what makes the architectural problem hard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The U.S. healthcare delivery system delivers care through a fragmented set of organizations: independent primary care practices, specialty-specific groups, hospital systems with multiple affiliated and unaffiliated practices, freestanding imaging centers, freestanding labs, infusion centers, durable-medical-equipment vendors, home-health agencies, retail pharmacies, mail-order pharmacies, behavioral-health providers (often separately contracted), and (depending on the patient's coverage) one or more payers running their own care-management programs. Each organization typically operates on its own EHR or practice-management system, with its own scheduling workflow, its own prior-authorization workflow, its own referral-receipt-and-tracking workflow, its own results-reporting workflow, its own patient-portal interface, and its own staff. The patient (or caregiver) is the de facto data integrator across all of this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Several attempts to fix this at the technology layer have been made over twenty years, with mixed results. Health information exchanges (HIEs) at the regional and state level have provided some cross-institution data sharing, with substantial variation in coverage, completeness, timeliness, and provider participation. <!-- TODO: verify; HIE coverage and effectiveness vary substantially by state and region; the Sequoia Project, eHealth Exchange, CommonWell Health Alliance, and Carequality have all worked to improve cross-institution interoperability with documented progress and ongoing gaps --> Direct Trust messaging, Carequality, CommonWell, and the broader TEFCA framework have established interoperability standards with growing adoption. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation and Carequality and CommonWell adoption rates have continued to evolve since the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions; specific adoption figures vary --> The 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking rules have substantially expanded patient and provider access to electronic health information, with associated FHIR API requirements at the EHR vendor level. <!-- TODO: verify; the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions and the FHIR-API requirements at the EHR vendor level have continued to roll out since the rule's effective dates; specific compliance status varies by EHR and provider --> The architectural reality, despite all of this, is that cross-institution data integration is still incomplete, still has substantial latency for some transitions, and still requires substantial care-coordinator labor to fill the gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital care-coordination tools, roughly the 2000s through the early 2010s, lived inside individual EHRs as work queues for case managers and care coordinators. The case manager logged into the EHR, looked at their queue, picked up the phone, called the patient or the next provider in the chain, documented the call back into the EHR, and moved on. The tools were institution-bound. The case manager could not see what was happening at the patient's other institutions. The patient could not see what the case manager was working on. The phone was the integration mechanism.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly the mid-2010s through the early 2020s, added patient-facing portal surfaces (where patients could see appointments, results, and messages within a single institution's footprint), cross-institution care-management platforms layered on HIEs and Direct messaging (used primarily by case managers, with limited patient-facing features), and care-navigation programs in specific specialty contexts (oncology navigation in cancer centers being the most mature example). The clinical evidence for some of these programs is meaningful, particularly in cancer care, where studies of nurse navigation programs have demonstrated improvements in time-to-treatment, treatment completion, patient experience, and (in some studies) outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for oncology navigation includes studies by Wagner et al., Carroll et al., and ongoing program evaluations including the Patient Navigation Research Program; specific outcome figures vary by program and population --> The fundamental constraint, though, was again labor: navigation programs are staff-intensive and reach a small fraction of the patients who would benefit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, as in the previous chapter 11 recipes, conversational AI that can handle the reactive logistics work and proactively surface gaps, combined with the FHIR-and-Cures-Act interoperability foundation that makes cross-institution data integration tractable in a way it was not five years ago. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance and careful data-sharing agreements with the patient's broader care network, can hold the patient's whole journey state across institutions, can surface the next step at the right moment, can handle the broad-middle of coordination work that human coordinators cannot reach, and can escalate to the human coordinators when human judgment is needed. The assistant is not a coordinator. The assistant is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the care-coordination workflow operate at a population scale that human-only coordination cannot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "case-manager work-queue inside one EHR" to "longitudinal-journey state spanning institutions with conversational interface for the patient and structured-output integration with the care team and the multi-institution integration layer." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the longitudinal-journey state (the only place in the patient's life where the whole journey is held coherently), the proactive gap detection (catching the prior auth that has stalled, the follow-up that was missed, the medication reconciliation that surfaced a duplicate), and the operational reach (extending care coordination from a few percent of the population to the broad middle that needs it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care episodes, active diagnoses, active medications, scheduled appointments, pending referrals, pending prior authorizations, recent lab and imaging results, conversation history), access to a structured library of journey templates (per common care episode: cancer-diagnosis-and-treatment, post-stroke-recovery, post-MI-recovery, joint-replacement, transplant-evaluation, complex-pediatric, pregnancy-and-postpartum, end-of-life, others), access to multi-institution integration tools (FHIR, HL7 v2 message stream, HIE query, Direct messaging, payer eligibility and prior-authorization APIs), and a careful set of tools for surfacing gaps, escalating to human coordinators, sending coordination messages on behalf of the patient (with patient consent), and tracking the journey forward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is bidirectional. Sometimes the patient initiates ("when is my next appointment? what is the prior auth status?"). Sometimes the assistant initiates per a journey-milestone trigger ("your biopsy is on Tuesday; here is what to expect; do you have questions?") or per a gap-detection trigger ("I noticed your follow-up labs were ordered four weeks ago and have not been done yet. Would you like help scheduling them?"). Sometimes a clinical-team-side event triggers a patient-facing communication ("the medical oncologist sent over a recommended treatment plan; would you like me to walk through it with you?"). The bidirectionality is a substantial part of the value: the patient does not have to remember to ask, because the assistant is watching the journey forward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Journey instantiation.** When a patient enters a care episode (newly-diagnosed cancer, post-discharge from a heart-failure admission, scheduled for a major surgery, etc.), the patient's care team or the institution's care-management team enrolls the patient and selects the appropriate journey template. The journey template captures the typical sequence of events, milestones, decision points, expected timeline, and common gaps for that journey. The instantiated journey holds the patient-specific values: the actual scheduled appointments, the actual referrals, the actual specialists, the actual medications, the actual care team. Skipping the journey instantiation produces an assistant that has access to data but no model of where the patient is in the journey.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institution data integration.** The assistant pulls the patient's data from the institution's primary EHR plus, where data-sharing agreements permit, from external institutions via HIE, Carequality/CommonWell/TEFCA, Direct messaging, payer APIs, or vendor-mediated integrations (e.g., pharmacy data via prescription-fill APIs, imaging data via PACS-bridge integrations, lab data via lab-network integrations). The integration is continuous, not point-in-time. The assistant's view of the patient is updated as data flows in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment, referral, and prior-authorization tracking.** The assistant tracks the lifecycle of every appointment (scheduled, confirmed, completed, no-show, rescheduled, cancelled), every referral (sent, received-by-receiver, scheduled, completed, results-back), and every prior authorization (submitted, in-review, approved, denied, expired). The lifecycle states are exposed to the patient in plain language ("your prior auth for the PET scan was approved on Tuesday; the scan is scheduled for Thursday at 10am at the imaging center") and to the care team in structured form.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gap detection.** The assistant runs continuous gap detection over the journey state. Categories include: stalled prior authorizations, overdue follow-ups, missed appointments, missed scheduled tests, medication-reconciliation conflicts (the patient is on two medications from different specialists that interact), duplicate-test risk, dropped referrals (sent but not received or scheduled), missing pre-procedure clearances, and timing risks (the next step in the journey is at risk of slipping). Gaps are categorized by severity and routed appropriately (patient-facing notification for low-severity, care-team alert for higher-severity, immediate escalation for critical).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-specialist information surfacing.** When the patient has a question that requires synthesizing information from multiple specialists, the assistant surfaces what is known across the care team. The synthesis is grounded in the actual records and is bounded by scope ("the medical oncologist's note from your visit on Monday says the recommended treatment plan is concurrent chemo and radiation starting in 4-6 weeks; the radiation oncology consultation is scheduled for next Wednesday; the medical oncologist's note also mentions discussing clinical trial eligibility, which they will go over at next Tuesday's follow-up").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication reconciliation support.** Across institutions and across pharmacy sources, the assistant maintains a reconciled view of the patient's medications. When discrepancies appear (a prescription was discontinued at one visit but was not communicated to the pharmacy that fills it, a new prescription duplicates an existing one, an active prescription was missed during the discharge medication reconciliation), the assistant surfaces them to the patient and to the appropriate clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Communication coordination.** With patient consent, the assistant can send messages to the patient's care team on the patient's behalf, can request information from one institution to share with another, can submit patient-completed forms, and can coordinate logistics across the team. The assistant's communications are auditable, attributable to the patient (with the assistant as the visible drafting tool), and reviewable by the patient before sending where appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Resource and benefits navigation.** When the patient's needs require resources outside the immediate care team (transportation to appointments, financial assistance, language services, durable medical equipment, home health, social services, legal aid for healthcare-related issues), the assistant routes to the appropriate institutional or community resource. Where the patient's needs require benefits navigation (recipe 11.5), the assistant routes with context attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver involvement.** Many complex-care patients have a designated family caregiver who participates in the care work. The assistant supports caregiver involvement with the patient's documented consent, with appropriate privacy controls, and with a clear distinction between patient-directed and caregiver-directed conversation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** The care team has visibility into the assistant's interactions with the patient through structured summaries (daily for high-acuity episodes, weekly for stable episodes, monthly for low-touch episodes). The assistant flags significant events to the appropriate human coordinator in real time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding.** Care episodes end. The assistant supports a structured off-boarding when the patient completes the journey, transitions to a different program, or no longer needs the level of support, with summary delivery to the broader care team and a clear path back if a new episode begins.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface and EHR access, and have it answer the patient's coordination questions. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no model of the journey.** A generalist LLM responds to whatever the patient asks. It has no model of what the patient is in the middle of, what should happen next, what is at risk of slipping, what gaps should be surfaced unprompted. The journey state and the journey-template-driven proactive logic are architectural primitives, not emergent properties of the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view across institutions.** Without explicit cross-institution data integration with normalized representation, the LLM either has access to one institution's data (and is blind to the others) or is asked to reason across structurally different data shapes from different institutions, which it does poorly. The integration layer with normalized FHIR-style representation is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates logistics when state is incomplete.** If the prior-authorization status is not actually retrievable, the LLM produces plausible-sounding answers about prior-authorization status that are wrong. Worse, the wrong answers feel correct enough that the patient acts on them. The state-grounded retrieval discipline is critical, with explicit "I don't know yet" responses when the state is genuinely unknown.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to engage proactively.** Most of the assistant's value is in proactive engagement (the prior auth has stalled, the follow-up is overdue, the medication reconciliation surfaced a duplicate). A reactive bot that only responds when the patient initiates is missing the central value proposition. The proactive engagement is driven by the gap-detection pipeline, not by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation across cross-institutional boundaries.** Some gaps require action by the patient's other institutions, where the assistant has no operational authority. The escalation pathways have to be explicit: which gaps escalate to which institutional coordinator, which gaps prompt a patient-facing call-the-clinic recommendation, which gaps trigger a care-management-team alert.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications across multiple data-sharing agreements.** Cross-institution data integration sits on top of HIPAA, the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking rules, the Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) where applicable, state-specific data-sharing rules, and any institution-to-institution data-sharing agreements (HIE participation agreements, Carequality/CommonWell agreements, point-to-point Direct messaging agreements). The audit, retention, access-control, and revocable-consent posture has to handle all of these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope when the patient asks for clinical interpretation.** Patients in complex care journeys frequently ask the assistant to interpret their pathology report, their imaging report, their lab results, their treatment plan. The assistant explains what scheduling and logistics flows from the result; it does not interpret clinical meaning. The boundary is delicate and the scope discipline is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient-versus-caregiver conversation.** When a caregiver is involved, the assistant has to know who it is talking to at any given moment and what that person's authorization scope is. Identity-and-authorization-aware conversation handling is part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-rule arithmetic problems.** Some coordination tasks involve clinical-rule arithmetic (eligibility for a clinical trial based on staging, eligibility for a program based on risk score, dosing-related coordination). The deterministic clinical-rule tools encapsulate the computation; the LLM does not freelance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of relationship preservation across a stressful journey.** Patients in complex care journeys are often exhausted, stressed, and emotionally fragile. The assistant's tone has to be calibrated for that reality: warm, calm, organized, not falsely cheerful, not coldly transactional, and never patronizing. The tone work is not optional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal memory, citation grounding. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institution data integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant's value depends on having a coherent view of the patient's care across the institutions involved. The integration layer with normalized representation, source attribution, freshness tracking, and graceful handling of partial data is part of the core architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Journey-template-as-code with care-management-leadership ownership.** Each common care episode has a structured journey template, owned by the appropriate care-management leadership, instantiated for each patient with patient-specific values, version-controlled, and reviewed periodically. The assistant operates within the journey template; deviations from the template are events that warrant attention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous gap detection with severity-based routing.** The gap-detection pipeline runs continuously over the journey state. Each gap category has a defined severity and a defined routing path. Gap-detection accuracy and latency are operational metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-institution communication and consent.** With patient consent, the assistant can communicate with institutions outside the primary deploying institution. Consent is granular, revocable, and auditable. The communication uses appropriate cross-institution channels (Direct messaging, FHIR-based messaging where supported, fax-replacement APIs where used, fallback to phone-based human handoff when electronic options fail).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver-aware conversation handling.** With patient-documented consent, the assistant supports caregiver participation. The identity-and-authorization-aware conversation handling distinguishes patient turns from caregiver turns, applies appropriate scope per role, and audits the participation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode lifecycle management.** Care episodes have beginnings, middles, and ends. The episode-lifecycle layer handles enrollment, active-management, transitions across phases of the journey, off-boarding, and re-enrollment. The lifecycle is tracked separately from the day-to-day conversation state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-of-record management.** The patient's care team is dynamic: specialists are added, primary clinicians change, care managers are assigned. The care-team-of-record model handles updates as the journey evolves and is the source of truth for who-to-route-to-when decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system event correlation.** Events from multiple institutions arrive asynchronously through different channels (FHIR subscriptions where available, HL7 v2 ADT and ORU messages, ORM messages, inbound Direct messages, HIE notifications, payer-side events for prior-auth status). The event correlation layer normalizes these into journey-state updates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The data-integration layer is the largest pre-deployment investment.** Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that the cross-institution data integration is the single longest-pole work item. Per-institution data-sharing-agreement negotiation, per-EHR FHIR-API enablement, HL7 v2 interface engineering, HIE-query integration, Direct-messaging mailbox provisioning, payer-API integration, and the normalization layer above all of it can take 12 to 24 months to implement at production quality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Latency and completeness vary across data sources.** Some sources are real-time (the institution's own EHR for inbound observations); some are near-real-time (HL7 ORU messages from external labs); some are batch (HIE document queries that pull C-CDAs on a daily or weekly basis); some are unreliable (faxes that arrive irregularly and require OCR and entity extraction to be useful). The assistant's view of the patient has freshness gaps that are worth acknowledging in the conversation rather than papering over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-reported information is essential and is also unreliable.** Patients know things the data does not show: what the specialist actually said, how they are actually feeling, what they are actually doing about the medication. The assistant integrates patient-reported information alongside data-derived information, with appropriate confidence labeling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The scope of "care coordination" is institutionally specific.** Some institutions define care coordination narrowly (within-institution scheduling and logistics). Some define it broadly (full cross-institution journey navigation). The deployment scope is one of the first decisions the institutional leadership makes; the architecture supports the chosen scope without overpromising.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver dynamics are real and consequential.** Family caregivers do an enormous amount of the coordination work. The institutional position on caregiver participation, the consent architecture, the communication-routing-when-multiple-people-are-involved, and the privacy posture are all delicate and important. Overpromising caregiver capabilities creates privacy violations; underdelivering frustrates caregivers who are already overburdened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural, linguistic, and health-literacy considerations are major.** Care coordination is hardest for patients with the least access to system-literacy. Spanish-language deployment, low-literacy plain-language content, and culturally-aware care-navigation patterns are not optional for a deployment serving the population that needs coordination most.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social determinants of health are part of the coordination reality.** Patients without transportation cannot make appointments scheduled across town. Patients with unstable housing cannot reliably receive mailed materials. Patients with limited English need language services. Patients without paid time off cannot attend midday appointments. The coordinator's recommendations are clinically reasonable and operationally only feasible to the extent they fit the patient's life. The institutional deployment includes social-determinants overlays where possible, with care-navigation handoffs to community resources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institution political dynamics matter.** Institutions are sometimes in competitive relationships, sometimes in collaborative relationships, sometimes in tension over patient flow. A coordination assistant that nominally serves the patient but operationally functions as a referral funnel for the deploying institution is a coordination assistant the patient will eventually distrust. The institutional ethics of patient-first coordination is reviewed by leadership, by legal, and (in some institutions) by patient advisory councils.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordination work has its own pace.** A heart-failure post-discharge journey runs on a fast clock (the readmission risk is highest in the first 30 days). A cancer-diagnosis journey has phases with very different paces (the diagnostic phase moves quickly; the active-treatment phase moves to specific protocols; the survivorship phase moves slowly). The assistant's engagement cadence respects the journey's natural pace and adapts as the patient transitions between phases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination errors are silent until they are loud.** A missed prior auth produces no immediate symptom; the patient just shows up to the appointment that has been cancelled. A missed follow-up lab produces no immediate symptom; the patient just continues on a regimen without the surveillance that should have happened. Most coordination failures are silent for weeks before they become visible. The gap-detection pipeline exists in part to surface them while they are still silent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is hard.** The patients who benefit most from coordination are the ones with the most complex journeys, but those are also the patients with the most clinical events, which makes pure-engagement-based outcome attribution unreliable. Comparison against matched cohorts of similar-complexity patients without coordination, or quasi-experimental analyses where institutional roll-out provides natural variation, is more credible than pre-post analyses on engaged patients alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature and the buy options vary substantially.** Several mature commercial care-coordination platforms operate at scale, with FHIR integration, HL7 v2 messaging, HIE connectivity, multi-institution support, and patient-facing surfaces. Most major institutions run a hybrid: vendor platform for the core multi-institution data integration and case-management workflow, in-house customization for the patient-facing AI conversational layer and the institution's specific journey templates, and integration with the institution's broader infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR maturity has changed the calculus.** EHR vendor support for FHIR R4 APIs is substantially more complete than it was five years ago, partly because the Cures Act information-blocking rule made it functionally required. Cross-institution data integration that would have required custom HL7 v2 interfaces and per-institution one-off engineering can now, in many cases, be done through standardized FHIR APIs with consistent resource representations. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 adoption has continued to roll out across major EHR vendors with substantial progress since the 21st Century Cures Act effective dates; specific coverage and consistency varies by EHR and by institutional configuration -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA is real but rolling out unevenly.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement provides a legal and technical framework for cross-institution data sharing under Qualified Health Information Network governance. Adoption varies by region and institution; institutions building care-coordination infrastructure should align their data-sharing approach with the TEFCA trajectory in their region. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation through QHINs has continued to progress; specific coverage and adoption varies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Oncology navigation has the strongest evidence base for AI augmentation.** The cancer-diagnosis-and-treatment journey is one of the most-studied care-coordination contexts; oncology nurse navigation programs have well-documented impact; AI augmentation of navigation has been an active area of product development and (in some institutions) clinical research. <!-- TODO: verify; AI-augmented oncology navigation has been an active area at major cancer centers and commercial platforms; specific outcome figures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transitional care has established protocols.** The 30-day post-discharge window, particularly for high-risk discharge categories (heart failure, COPD, post-surgical, post-stroke), has well-established care-transition protocols (Care Transitions Intervention, Project RED, others) that map to journey-template-based assistant deployments. <!-- TODO: verify; transitional care protocols have well-documented evidence; specific protocol implementations vary by institution -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-facing AI is increasingly accepted in care-coordination contexts.** Patients have grown comfortable with conversational interfaces in healthcare contexts; institutions have established disclosure, consent, and oversight norms; the regulatory landscape has stabilized somewhat for non-diagnostic patient-facing software. <!-- TODO: verify; patient acceptance and regulatory positioning of patient-facing healthcare AI continues to evolve --> Care-coordination AI, because it is operationally focused rather than clinically diagnostic, sits at a relatively well-understood position in the regulatory framework.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human coordination is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for the broad chronic-coordination majority, with human navigators or care managers for high-acuity episodes, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI handles the routine logistics while the human focuses where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
